[text [title}Julian and Maddalo{]
      [date}1819{]
      [author [dates [birth}1792{][death}1822{]]}Percy Bysshe Shelley{]
      [encodingStmt}Encoded in 2011-2012 by Wendell Piez as a 
      demonstration of LMNL syntax. Range and annotation types should be 
      fairly self-explanatory (and TEI-like), with a few additions such
      as 'verse-para' for verse paragraphs (which sometimes interrupt lines).{]
      [editorialStmt}A correction to a long-standing misattribution
      of quotes was made in lines 608-615.{]}
  [body}
    [verse-para}[lg}[l [n}1{n]}I rode one evening with Count Maddalo{l]
      [l [n}2{n]}Upon the bank of land which breaks the flow{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}3{n]}Of Adria towards Venice: a bare strand{l]
      [l [n}4{n]}Of hillocks, heaped from ever-shifting sand,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}5{n]}Matted with thistles and amphibious weeds,{l]
      [l [n}6{n]}Such as from earth’s embrace the salt ooze breeds,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}7{n]}Is this; an uninhabited sea-side,{l]
      [l [n}8{n]}Which the lone fisher, when his nets are dried,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}9{n]}Abandons; and no other object breaks{l]
      [l [n}10{n]}The waste, but one dwarf tree and some few stakes{l]
      [l [n}11{n]}Broken and unrepaired, and the tide makes{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}12{n]}A narrow space of level sand thereon,{l]
      [l [n}13{n]}Where ’twas our wont to ride while day went down.{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}14{n]}This ride was my delight. I love all waste{l]
      [l [n}15{n]}And solitary places; where we taste{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}16{n]}The pleasure of believing what we see{l]
      [l [n}17{n]}Is boundless, as we wish our souls to be:{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}18{n]}And such was this wide ocean, and this shore{l]
      [l [n}19{n]}More barren than its billows; and yet more{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}20{n]}Than all, with a remembered friend I love{l]
      [l [n}21{n]}To ride as then I rode;—for the winds drove{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}22{n]}The living spray along the sunny air{l]
      [l [n}23{n]}Into our faces; the blue heavens were bare,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}24{n]}Stripped to their depths by the awakening north;{l]
      [l [n}25{n]}And, from the waves, sound like delight broke forth{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}26{n]}Harmonising with solitude, and sent{l]
      [l [n}27{n]}Into our hearts aereal merriment.{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}28{n]}So, as we rode, we talked; and the swift thought,{l]
      [l [n}29{n]}Winging itself with laughter, lingered not,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}30{n]}But flew from brain to brain,—such glee was ours,{l]
      [l [n}31{n]}Charged with light memories of remembered hours,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}32{n]}None slow enough for sadness: till we came{l]
      [l [n}33{n]}Homeward, which always makes the spirit tame.{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}34{n]}This day had been cheerful but cold, and now{l]
      [l [n}35{n]}The sun was sinking, and the wind also.{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}36{n]}Our talk grew somewhat serious, as may be{l]
      [l [n}37{n]}Talk interrupted with such raillery{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}38{n]}As mocks itself, because it cannot scorn{l]
      [l [n}39{n]}The thoughts it would extinguish: —’twas forlorn,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}40{n]}Yet pleasing, such as once, so poets tell,{l]
      [l [n}41{n]}The devils held within the dales of Hell{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}42{n]}Concerning God, freewill and destiny:{l]
      [l [n}43{n]}Of all that earth has been or yet may be,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}44{n]}All that vain men imagine or believe,{l]
      [l [n}45{n]}Or hope can paint or suffering may achieve,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}46{n]}We descanted; and I (for ever still{l]
      [l [n}47{n]}Is it not wise to make the best of ill?){l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}48{n]}Argued against despondency, but pride{l]
      [l [n}49{n]}Made my companion take the darker side.{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}50{n]}The sense that he was greater than his kind{l]
      [l [n}51{n]}Had struck, methinks, his eagle spirit blind{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}52{n]}By gazing on its own exceeding light.{l]
      [l [n}53{n]}Meanwhile the sun paused ere it should alight,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}54{n]}Over the horizon of the mountains;—Oh,{l]
      [l [n}55{n]}How beautiful is sunset, when the glow{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}56{n]}Of Heaven descends upon a land like thee,{l]
      [l [n}57{n]}Thou Paradise of exiles, Italy!{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}58{n]}Thy mountains, seas and vineyards, and the towers{l]
      [l [n}59{n]}Of cities they encircle!—it was ours{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}60{n]}To stand on thee, beholding it: and then,{l]
      [l [n}61{n]}Just where we had dismounted, the Count’s men{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}62{n]}Were waiting for us with the gondola.—{l]
      [l [n}63{n]}As those who pause on some delightful way{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}64{n]}Though bent on pleasant pilgrimage, we stood{l]
      [l [n}65{n]}Looking upon the evening, and the flood{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}66{n]}Which lay between the city and the shore,{l]
      [l [n}67{n]}Paved with the image of the sky … the hoar{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}68{n]}And aery Alps towards the North appeared{l]
      [l [n}69{n]}Through mist, an heaven-sustaining bulwark reared{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}70{n]}Between the East and West; and half the sky{l]
      [l [n}71{n]}Was roofed with clouds of rich emblazonry{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}72{n]}Dark purple at the zenith, which still grew{l]
      [l [n}73{n]}Down the steep West into a wondrous hue{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}74{n]}Brighter than burning gold, even to the rent{l]
      [l [n}75{n]}Where the swift sun yet paused in his descent{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}76{n]}Among the many-folded hills: they were{l]
      [l [n}77{n]}Those famous Euganean hills, which bear,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}78{n]}As seen from Lido thro’ the harbour piles,{l]
      [l [n}79{n]}The likeness of a clump of peaked isles—{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}80{n]}And then—as if the Earth and Sea had been{l]
      [l [n}81{n]}Dissolved into one lake of fire, were seen{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}82{n]}Those mountains towering as from waves of flame{l]
      [l [n}83{n]}Around the vaporous sun, from which there came{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}84{n]}The inmost purple spirit of light, and made{l]
      [l [n}85{n]}Their very peaks transparent. [q [who}Maddalo{who]}Ere it fade,{q]{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}86{n]}Said my companion, [q [who}Maddalo{who]}I will
        show you soon{l]
      [l [n}87{n]}A better station{q]—so, o’er the lagune{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}88{n]}We glided; and from that funereal bark{l]
      [l [n}89{n]}I leaned, and saw the city, and could mark{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}90{n]}How from their many isles, in evening’s gleam,{l]
      [l [n}91{n]}Its temples and its palaces did seem{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}92{n]}Like fabrics of enchantment piled to Heaven.{l]
      [l [n}93{n]}I was about to speak, when—[q [who}Maddalo{who]}We
        are even{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}94{n]}Now at the point I meant,{q] said Maddalo,{l]
      [l [n}95{n]}And bade the gondolieri cease to row.{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [q [who}Maddalo{who]}[l [n}96{n]}Look, Julian, on the west,
        and listen well{l]
      [l [n}97{n]}If you hear not a deep and heavy bell.{l]{q]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}98{n]}I looked, and saw between us and the sun{l]
      [l [n}99{n]}A building on an island; such a one{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}100{n]}As age to age might add, for uses vile,{l]
      [l [n}101{n]}A windowless, deformed and dreary pile;{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}102{n]}And on the top an open tower, where hung{l]
      [l [n}103{n]}A bell, which in the radiance swayed and swung;{l]
      [l [n}104{n]}We could just hear its hoarse and iron tongue:{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}105{n]}The broad sun sunk behind it, and it tolled{l]
      [l [n}106{n]}In strong and black relief.—[q [who}Maddalo{who]}What we behold{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}107{n]}Shall be the madhouse and its belfry tower,{l]{q]
      [l [n}108{n]}Said Maddalo, [q [who}Maddalo{who]}and ever at
        this hour{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}109{n]}Those who may cross the water, hear that bell{l]
      [l [n}110{n]}Which calls the maniacs, each one from his cell,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}111{n]}To vespers.{q]—[q [who}Julian{who]}As much skill as need to pray{l]
      [l [n}112{n]}In thanks or hope for their dark lot have they{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}113{n]}To their stern maker,{q] I replied. [q [who}Maddalo{who]}O ho!{l]
      [l [n}114{n]}You talk as in years past,{q] said
        Maddalo.{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [q [who}Maddalo{who]}[l [n}115{n]}’Tis strange men change
        not. You were ever still{l]
      [l [n}116{n]}Among Christ’s flock a perilous infidel,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}117{n]}A wolf for the meek lambs—if you can’t swim{l]
      [l [n}118{n]}Beware of Providence.{q] I looked on him,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}119{n]}But the gay smile had faded in his eye.{l]
      [l [n}120{n]}[q [who}Maddalo{who]}And such,{q]—he cried, [q [who}Maddalo{who]}is our
        mortality,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}121{n]}And this must be the emblem and the sign{l]
      [l [n}122{n]}Of what should be eternal and divine!—{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}123{n]}And like that black and dreary bell, the soul,{l]
      [l [n}124{n]}Hung in a heaven-illumined tower, must toll{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}125{n]}Our thoughts and our desires to meet below{l]
      [l [n}126{n]}Round the rent heart and pray—as madmen do{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}127{n]}For what? they know not,—till the night of death{l]
      [l [n}128{n]}As sunset that strange vision, severeth{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}129{n]}Our memory from itself, and us from all{l]
      [l [n}130{n]}We sought and yet were baffled.{q] I
        recall{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}131{n]}The sense of what he said, although I mar{l]
      [l [n}132{n]}The force of his expressions. The broad star{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}133{n]}Of day meanwhile had sunk behind the hill,{l]
      [l [n}134{n]}And the black bell became invisible,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}135{n]}And the red tower looked gray, and all between{l]
      [l [n}136{n]}The churches, ships and palaces were seen{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}137{n]}Huddled in gloom;—into the purple sea{l]
      [l [n}138{n]}The orange hues of heaven sunk silently.{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}139{n]}We hardly spoke, and soon the gondola{l]
      [l [n}140{n]}Conveyed me to my lodging by the way.{l]{lg]{verse-para]
    [verse-para}[lg}[l [n}141{n]}The following morn was rainy, cold, and dim:{l]
      [l [n}142{n]}Ere Maddalo arose, I called on him,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}143{n]}And whilst I waited with his child I played;{l]
      [l [n}144{n]}A lovelier toy sweet Nature never made;{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}145{n]}A serious, subtle, wild, yet gentle being,{l]
      [l [n}146{n]}Graceful without design and unforeseeing,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}147{n]}With eyes—Oh speak not of her eyes!—which seem{l]
      [l [n}148{n]}Twin mirrors of Italian Heaven, yet gleam{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}149{n]}With such deep meaning, as we never see{l]
      [l [n}150{n]}But in the human countenance: with me{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}151{n]}She was a special favourite: I had nursed{l]
      [l [n}152{n]}Her fine and feeble limbs when she came first{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}153{n]}To this bleak world; and she yet seemed to know{l]
      [l [n}154{n]}On second sight her ancient playfellow,{l]
      [l [n}155{n]}Less changed than she was by six months or so;{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}156{n]}For after her first shyness was worn out{l]
      [l [n}157{n]}We sate there, rolling billiard balls about,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}158{n]}When the Count entered. Salutations past—{l]
      [q [who}Julian{who]}[l [n}159{n]}The word you spoke last
        night might well have cast{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}160{n]}A darkness on my spirit—if man be{l]
      [l [n}161{n]}The passive thing you say, I should not see{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}162{n]}Much harm in the religions and old saws{l]
      [l [n}163{n]}(Tho’ I may never own such leaden laws){l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}164{n]}Which break a teachless nature to the yoke:{l]
      [l [n}165{n]}Mine is another faith.{q]—thus much I
        spoke{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}166{n]}And noting he replied not, added: [q [who}Julian{who]}See{l]
      [l [n}167{n]}This lovely child, blithe, innocent and free;{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}168{n]}She spends a happy time with little care,{l]
      [l [n}169{n]}While we to such sick thoughts subjected are{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}170{n]}As came on you last night. It is our will{l]
      [l [n}171{n]}That thus enchains us to permitted ill—{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}172{n]}We might be otherwise—we might be all{l]
      [l [n}173{n]}We dream of happy, high, majestical.{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}174{n]}Where is the love, beauty, and truth we seek,{l]
      [l [n}175{n]}But in our mind? and if we were not weak{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}176{n]}Should we be less in deed than in desire?{l]{q]
      [q [who}Maddalo{who]}[l [n}177{n]}Ay, if we were not
        weak—and we aspire{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}178{n]}How vainly to be strong!{q] said
        Maddalo:{l]
      [l [n}179{n]}[q [who}Maddalo{who]}You talk Utopia.{q] [q [who}Julian{who]}It remains to
        know,{q]{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}180{n]}I then rejoined, [q [who}Julian{who]}and those
        who try may find{l]
      [l [n}181{n]}How strong the chains are which our spirit bind;{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}182{n]}Brittle perchance as straw … We are assured{l]
      [l [n}183{n]}Much may be conquered, much may be endured,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}184{n]}Of what degrades and crushes us. We know{l]
      [l [n}185{n]}That we have power over ourselves to do{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}186{n]}And suffer—what, we know not till we try;{l]
      [l [n}187{n]}But something nobler than to live and die—{l]
      [l [n}188{n]}So taught those kings of old philosophy{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}189{n]}Who reigned, before Religion made men blind;{l]
      [l [n}190{n]}And those who suffer with their suffering kind{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}191{n]}Yet feel their faith, religion.{q] [q [who}Maddalo{who]}My dear friend,{q]{l]
      [l [n}192{n]}Said Maddalo, [q [who}Maddalo{who]}my judgement
        will not bend{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}193{n]}To your opinion, though I think you might{l]
      [l [n}194{n]}Make such a system refutation-tight{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}195{n]}As far as words go. I knew one like you{l]
      [l [n}196{n]}Who to this city came some months ago,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}197{n]}With whom I argued in this sort, and he{l]
      [l [n}198{n]}Is now gone mad,—and so he answered me,—{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}199{n]}Poor fellow! but if you would like to go,{l]
      [l [n}200{n]}We’ll visit him, and his wild talk will show{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}201{n]}How vain are such aspiring theories.{l]{q]
      [q [who}Julian{who]}[l [n}202{n]}I hope to prove the
        induction otherwise,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}203{n]}And that a want of that true theory, still,{l]
      [l [n}204{n]}Which seeks a [soCalled}soul of
        goodness{soCalled] in things ill{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}205{n]}Or in himself or others, has thus bowed{l]
      [l [n}206{n]}His being—there are some by nature proud,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}207{n]}Who patient in all else demand but this—{l]
      [l [n}208{n]}To love and be beloved with gentleness;{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}209{n]}And being scorned, what wonder if they die{l]
      [l [n}210{n]}Some living death? this is not destiny{l]
    {lg]
    [l [n}211{n]}But man’s own wilful ill.{q]{verse-para][verse-para}As thus I spoke{l]
    [lg}
      [l [n}212{n]}Servants announced the gondola, and we{l]
      [l [n}213{n]}Through the fast-falling rain and high-wrought sea{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}214{n]}Sailed to the island where the madhouse stands.{l]
      [l [n}215{n]}We disembarked. The clap of tortured hands,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}216{n]}Fierce yells and howlings and lamentings keen,{l]
      [l [n}217{n]}And laughter where complaint had merrier been,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}218{n]}Moans, shrieks, and curses, and blaspheming prayers{l]
      [l [n}219{n]}Accosted us. We climbed the oozy stairs{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}220{n]}Into an old courtyard. I heard on high,{l]
      [l [n}221{n]}Then, fragments of most touching melody,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}222{n]}But looking up saw not the singer there—{l]
      [l [n}223{n]}Through the black bars in the tempestuous air{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}224{n]}I saw, like weeds on a wrecked palace growing,{l]
      [l [n}225{n]}Long tangled locks flung wildly forth, and flowing,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}226{n]}Of those who on a sudden were beguiled{l]
      [l [n}227{n]}Into strange silence, and looked forth and smiled{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}228{n]}Hearing sweet sounds. Then I: [q [who}Julian{who]}Methinks there were{l]
      [l [n}229{n]}A cure of these with patience and kind care,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}230{n]}If music can thus move … but what is he{l]
      [l [n}231{n]}Whom we seek here?{q] [q [who}Maddalo{who]}Of his sad history{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}232{n]}I know but this,{q] said Maddalo: [q [who}Maddalo{who]}he came{l]
      [l [n}233{n]}To Venice a dejected man, and fame{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}234{n]}Said he was wealthy, or he had been so;{l]
      [l [n}235{n]}Some thought the loss of fortune wrought him woe;{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}236{n]}But he was ever talking in such sort{l]
      [l [n}237{n]}As you do—far more sadly—he seemed hurt,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}238{n]}Even as a man with his peculiar wrong,{l]
      [l [n}239{n]}To hear but of the oppression of the strong,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}240{n]}Or those absurd deceits (I think with you{l]
      [l [n}241{n]}In some respects, you know) which carry through{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}242{n]}The excellent impostors of this earth{l]
      [l [n}243{n]}When they outface detection—he had worth,{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}244{n]}Poor fellow! but a humorist in his way{q]—{l]
      [l [n}245{n]}[q [who}Julian{who]}Alas, what drove him mad?{q] [q [who}Maddalo{who]}I cannot
        say:{l]
    {lg]
    [lg}
      [l [n}246{n]}A lady came with him from France, and when{l]
